description.en: Energy System Information Model (ESIM) is a domain specific model that provides information of the urban and building energy system including the automation and control systems. It comprises functional, structural and physical descriptions of the systems as master data and additional operational data.

comment.undefined: EAS Identifier Concept
A medium is a substance or material which is used for a particular purpose or in order to produce a particular effect.
Mean time to repair
A space or group of spaces with ventilation requirements maintained by a ventilation system
A geothermal heat pump or ground source heat pump (GSHP) is a central heating and/or cooling system that transfers heat to or from the ground.
Mean time to failures
A space or group of spaces with cooling requirements maintained by a cooling system
A space or group of spaces within a building with heating, cooling, and ventilating requirements which can be maintain by a HVAC system
An ASHP that absorbs heat from outside air and releases it inside the building as hot water
Tariffs charged by energy providers for supplied energy
Adsorption Chiller is able to make chilled water with low temperature (65??100?) hot water. It uses solid sorption materials instead of liquid solutions.
Energy storage is the capture of energy produced at one time for use at a later time.
A solar-assisted heat pump (SAHP) is a machine that represents the integration of a heat pump and thermal solar panels in a single integrated system.
A water source heat pump where the thermal energy is transferred from the water constituting one medium to the water constituting another medium
Mean time to first failure
An air source heat pump (ASHP) is a system which transfers heat from outside to inside a building, or vice versa.
Hazard or failure rate ? (in h^-1 or y^-1)
Energy tariff refunded by providers for recovered energy through e.g. solar collectors
Mean time between failures
A chiller that uses an electrically driven mechanical compressor to force a refrigerant around the system
A water source heat pump where the thermal energy is transferred from the water constituting one medium (often a heat transfer circuit) to the air constituting another medium

An Exhaust Air Heat Pump (EAHP) extracts heat from the exhaust air of a building and transfers the heat to the supply air, hot tap water and/or hydronic heating system (underfloor heating, radiators).
A space or group of spaces with heating requirements maintained by a heating system
A chiller that uses a heat source such as steam or hot water to move the refrigerant around the system
Uses flowing water as source or sink for heat
A wind turbine is a device that converts the wind's kinetic energy into electrical power.
An ASHP that absorbs heat from outside air and releases it inside the building as hot air
A space or group of spaces within a building without heating, cooling, and ventilating requirements which can be maintain by a HVAC system

label.undefined: District electrical and heat supply system

comment.undefined: Flowing water creates energy that can be captured and turned into electricity. This is called hydroelectric power or hydropower. The most common type of hydroelectric power plant uses a dam on a river to store water in a reservoir.
The energy mix is the group of different primary energy sources from which secondary energy for direct use - usually electricity - is produced.
